payload.why_forbidden: OOP is the opposite of functional programming
payload.alternative: Use pure functions and function composition

payload.why_forbidden: Type aliases are more functional and composable
payload.alternative: Use type aliases and type inference

payload.why_forbidden: All functions must be curried for composition
payload.alternative: Curry all functions: (a: string) => (b: number) => result

payload.pattern: Creating index.ts files that re-export modules
payload.why_forbidden: Barrel files are the enemy of tree shaking and clarity
payload.alternative: Import directly from the source file

payload.why_forbidden: TypeScript already provides all type information. JSDoc is redundant noise
payload.alternative: Let the code speak. Use Envoy comments for actual insights

payload.why_forbidden: Violates modularity, creates hidden dependencies, leaves orphan code
payload.alternative: One function per file, in its own folder
examples: // utils.ts with processData, validateData, transformData all in one file

payload.pattern: Using classes anywhere, even in examples
payload.why_forbidden: Classes are OOP. We do FP. NO EXCEPTIONS
examples: // Example: class Calculator // NO! Not even in comments!

payload.why_forbidden: Mutations destroy predictability and create bugs
payload.alternative: Create new data structures with spread or Toolsmith functions

payload.pattern: Using loops instead of functional constructs
payload.why_forbidden: Loops are imperative and require mutable state

payload.pattern: Creating new tech debt with TODO/FIXME comments
payload.why_forbidden: Tech debt is NOT allowed. Do it right the first time

payload.pattern: Making assumptions instead of asking for clarification
payload.why_forbidden: Assumptions create messes that take weeks to fix

payload.pattern: Writing tests that always pass like assert(true)
payload.alternative: Write real assertions that verify actual behavior
